A chart to understand: Bitcoin's legal status around the world
Abstract: In addition to the price correction triggered by the natural properties of speculative properties, the tragic decline of this round of digital currency is also not unrelated to the risk of supervision of the enemy of the enemy.
From the visual map, the attitude of the Eastern countries towards Bitcoin is more conservative than the West, and the countries that occupy the world's main body are still waiting for the legitimacy of digital currency, which means that the "black swan risk" is still very large.
* This article is from Wall Street News (WeChat ID:wallstreetcn), editor Wang Mu. More exciting information Please log on to wallstreet.com or download the Wall Street News app. *
With the regulatory storm in major bitcoin markets such as China, South Korea and the European Union, the global digital currency led by bitcoin has been bloody washed this week, and the price of bitcoin fell below the psychological level of $1m on Tuesday, and its biggest one-day decline in three years.
In addition to the price correction triggered by the natural properties of speculative properties, the tragic decline of this round of digital currency has also not been unrelated to the regulatory risk of the long-standing "Over the Sea enemy".
At this important juncture, visual big data site HowMuch.net has produced a map that demonstrates Bitcoin's legitimacy and regulation in countries around the world.
As shown in the figure below, green represents the legal market of Bitcoin; orange represents the neutral market, although it has not yet been publicly legalized Bitcoin status, but there is no major use restriction; light pink represents a restricted market, that is, the local government tries to use the digital currency through red-red line policy or regulation; the dark-pink color is defined as illegal countries on behalf of Bitcoin; and gray is a country that has not yet commented.
(Photo from HowMuch.Net visualization team on November 15th)
The article pointed out that it can be seen from the distribution of green color blocks in the middle of the picture, and the attitude of the Eastern countries in the traditional sense towards Bitcoin is more conservative than the West.
Russia is currently the largest country that defines Bitcoin as the largest illegal country, and China is one of the largest restricted markets for Bitcoin, and India has no comment on Bitcoin and has not yet issued relevant policies.
North America and Western Europe are more concentrated in the regions with the highest acceptance of Bitcoin, the distribution of green blocks.
The views of Bitcoin in the Middle East and Latin America are clearly differentiated, and the distribution of color blocks in these regions is more mixed.
Among them, Iraq, Iran, Turkey, Brazil are legal bitcoin markets, Afghanistan, Pakistan, Saudi Arabia, Egypt, Bolivia and other countries have a certain degree of restrictions on their transactions and use, and more Latin American countries have not spoken out on Bitcoin.
In the light of the above data, in a total of 99 countries (or 40%) of the 246 countries in the world, there are no restrictions on the trading and use of Bitcoin, that is, the green and orange-yellow areas.
Seven countries (or 3%) are constrained markets (light pink), 10 countries (or 4%) define Bitcoin as illegal (dark pink), and 130 countries (or more than 53%) have not yet more treatment of digital currency information (grey).
This shows that countries that account for global entities (53%, more than half) are still waiting for the legitimacy of the digital currency led by Bitcoin, and also represents the "black swan risk" of Bitcoin.
The article believes that global regulators do not fully understand the emerging category of digital currencies, and may be the main reason why most countries have not yet made statements.
Although Bitcoin's "popland" has grown exponentially since last year does not represent interest in all countries, and some countries may be concerned that local fiat currencies are under threat as a result, or more worried about digital currencies being exploited by criminal organizations.
Wall Street has written a detailed summary of the international regulatory news against Bitcoin since last week, including China's start to crack down on the OTC exchanges' centralized online platforms and mobile apps, South Korea is still considering closing digital currency exchanges, the EU believes that bitcoin has not been widely accepted and warned investors to "lost the risk of losing blood."
Wall Street News Editor-in-Chief's Selected "Reading News | 2018: The Global Central Mother Opens the Year of Digital Currency?" has mentioned that from the perspective of regulation, acceptance / criticism, and adoption, 2018 will become the first year of digital currency for global central banks.
Russia and other major powers have criticized Bitcoin's legitimacy, which is actually to give way to the official issuance of digital currency.
