Scientists from China Air Force Engineering University study laser satellite for removing space junk
Chinese scientists have made a bold and innovative proposal to use large lasers to clean up the messy Earth's orbit and destroy old satellites as well as its sky junk.
According to the U.S. Newsweek website reported on November 15th, researchers at the Chinese Air Force Engineering University have written a paper entitled "Space-based laser removal of small-scale space debris variable orbit model research", which describes how space debris can be irradiated by laser to smaller, less harmful fragments.
According to the report, space waste has been a concern for the International Space Agency for many years, and the US space agency has considered a variety of options to track, detect and remove man-made debris.
Ways to remove large-scale space debris include giant networks used to clear and collect waste, as well as magnets that can be used to suck them out of orbit. Chinese scientists have conducted laser simulation studies to conclude that this would be an effective way to clean up Earth's orbit.
The paper's summary said: "(Mang simulation research) provides the necessary theoretical basis for the application of space-based laser space debris removal technology."
A 2014 study by U.S. defense giant Lockheed Martin found that for satellites operating in orbit, there are about 200 threats a day.
The high-speed debris moving along Earth's orbit is seen as a serious threat to future space missions, described by experts at the European Space Agency as "a deadly chain of threats over the past year, with high-speed debris continuing to increase."
According to the U.S. "Volkswagen Machinery" website reported on January 17th, space is basically empty, but next to Earth is becoming more and more crowded. Each satellite we send into space will eventually become a piece of debris that orbits the Earth, and over time, these debris will pile up.
The more debris, the higher the chance that a satellite that is still functioning is hit by the debris, which in turn damages or destroys a multimillion-dollar investment.
All space agencies have plans to remove space debris in the future.
NASA is considering reducing the speed of debris with jet gas to get it out of orbit, and Europe is considering launching a satellite carrying a large network to capture debris and bring back to Earth, and Japan's idea is to capture debris with an electric chain.
At present, China has also proposed a solution to space junk, that is, using a large laser to knock floating space waste into less harmful small fragments.
According to a paper published in the German monthly "Optico" by a group of researchers at the Chinese Air Force Engineering University, installing such a laser on a satellite would be able to effectively clean up space, at least according to the simulation results.
The only way to prove the effectiveness is to test it, and there is currently no arrangement for such a mission, but perhaps sooner or later someone will install a laser on a satellite and send it into space.
Once that's done, we can finally start eliminating the problem of space junk once and for all.
(Compiled / Hu Jing, Wang Haifang)
