After the Dust in the High Court's supply of drug funding for the NHS, patients will be able to receive "transformative" HIV prevention treatments starting in September.
NHS England announced that Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP), a drug that could be taken before sex, has been shown to reduce the risk of infection in at-risk populations by about 86 per cent. Now the health service will now deliver the drug to 10,000 people through a three-year preliminary trial.
It agreed to fund the trial after the Court of Appeal upheld the High Court ruling last year. The ruling said the NHS was entitled to pay for PrEP despite the NHS's claim that local authorities should fund the drug.
