Sexual health clinics in places such as London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be the first to register sexual health clinics for people. More clinics will be added in October, followed by a full implementation in England in April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an HIV drug that is taken before sex to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
Trials have shown that PrEP can significantly reduce HIV transmission in people at risk of infection.
Taking PrEP before sex means there are enough specific drugs in the human body to prevent HIV infection.
The drug can be taken daily or two hours before sexual intercourse.
Those eligible for treatment include gay, bisexual men, transgender people, and people with HIV who have not been successfully treated.
The clinic will determine whether participants who are eligible and agree to the trial, including men, women, transgender people and their sexual partner HIV status is unknown.
People who live in England and register GPs can also sign up at sexual health clinics where they attend locally.
The scheme will cost £10m, while the NHS England branch has signed a contract to procure the drugs this week after making international competitive purchases.
The trial is designed to assess the full potential of PrEP by collecting clinical evidence on how it is positioned, absorbed and implemented on a large sample basis.
Mr Stevens said: “This major new intervention should complement and reinforce HIV prevention in a wide range and increasingly successful.
This is yet another milestone in more than three decades of actions worth making progress in addressing the major health challenges of humanity. ”
Depola King, chief executive of the UK AIDS Trust Fund (NAT), said: "This is a critical time to fight AIDS.
