Does meat, dairy and chocolate help alleviate inflammatory bowel disease (IBD)?
Meat and chocolate may sound like a nightmare for your digestive system.
But a new study shows the opposite: a diet rich in meat protein and dairy products can help relieve associated symptoms in patients with inflammatory bowel disease.
The incurable disease has a life impact on about 1.3 million Americans and about 30 million Britons, leading to stomach cramps and bloating, recurrent or hemorrhagic diarrhoea, weight loss and extreme fatigue, among other things.
Researchers at the University of Washington would generally recommend that patients avoid eating meat and dairy products to relieve symptoms, but the researchers found that the protein's key amino acid - tryptophan helps promote immune cell growth, and these cells enhance gut tolerance.
Lead researcher Dr Marco Colonna explains that immune cells patrol the gut to ensure harmful microbes hidden in food do not creep into the body.
Maintain a balance between cells that cause inflammation and those that improve tolerance, protecting the body without damaging all kinds of sensitive and vulnerable tissues.
When the equilibrium state is too skewed towards inflammation, inflammatory bowel disease may occur.
A body of immunity was found in experiments that propulsing immunity in mice that carry special bacteria.
Bacteria need tryptophan (an component of the protein) to form the appearance of the cell.
Professor Colonna said: "We have a link between a bacterial population (which is a normal part of the gut microbiota) and the development of cell populations that can promote tolerance.
The more trytophan the mice in their diet, the more immune cells they have.
He suggested that if humans used the same method, namely Lululp Lactobacillus and a diet rich in tryptophan, might form a more tolerant, less inflammatory gut environment.
Postdoctoral researcher Luisa Cervantes-Barrawas studied a immune cell that enhances tolerance, and when she found that a group of mice had such cells, but another group of the same strain was fed separately.
She suspects this difference is related to the community of gut microbes in mice (referring to bacteria, viruses and fungi that typically live within the gastrointestinal tract).
DNA sequencing of the mice's cholesterol found that six bacterial populations were present in mice with immune cells, but mice without immune cells did not.
The mice were kept in a sterile environment, so they lacked gut microbes and could not appear this immune cell, and Lactobacillus was present to produce immune cells.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers culture Lactobacillus in the fluid and then transfer a small amount of fluid without bacteria to immature immune cells isolated from mice.
The immune cells develop into cells with tolerance.
When the active ingredient is purified from the liquid, it can be shown that the active ingredient is a byproduct of tryptophan metabolism, called indole-3-lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in mice's feed, the number of such cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the inmate levels were halved, the number of cells was halved.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explains that people, like mice, have the same cells that enhance tolerance, and most of us have Lulc Lactobacillus in our gastrointestinal tract.
Whether humans can induce the inmate-of-try by-products from Lactobacillus in the body, like the mice in the experiment, induce the cell development, and are not currently known, but genetic defects related to tryptophan are found in patients with inflammatory bowel disease.
“The development of these cells may be exactly what we want to get, because these cells can control the inflammatory response on the surface of the gut. ”
