Recently, everyone is discussing what has the recent changes in real estate policy, is it that real estate policy is loosened again? The diversification of land policy supply providers will not let house prices decline?
However, when we are worried about real estate prices, worried about macroeconomic regulation, worried about the future trend of the real estate market, the People's Daily wrote again, the last time we devoted to the "People's Daily" review on the regulation of real estate regulation, and now the "People's Daily" wrote a more serious topic than not buying a house, this is even if you can afford to buy a house, debt?
Today, we're going to talk about the more serious problem than buying a house: repayment.
China's growing housing debt crisis
The overseas edition of the People's Daily published an opinion article on November 17th, "Profit for Credit and Loans. Worries for Youth", according to the data in the article, in November 2017, the "Three-quarter China deleveraging Process Report" released by the National Financial and Development Laboratory and the National Balance Sheet Research Center of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences pointed out that the leverage ratio of the residential sector still continued to rise, from 47.4% in the second quarter of 2017 to 48.6% in the third quarter of the quarter, up 1.3 percentage points, and rose by 3.8 percentage points in the first three quarters of 2017.
The proportion of debt in the entire real economy has increased, and the leverage ratio has risen rapidly.
Studies have shown that the liabilities of Chinese households in financial institutions are dominated by consumer loans, accounting for about 2/3 of residents' liabilities, which is about twice that of operating loans.
Among them, in consumer loans, medium and long-term loans dominated by housing loans account for about eighty percent, but from the incremental point of view, short-term consumer loans are growing faster, higher than medium- and long-term loans.
In addition, China's household debt rate only counts the total amount of credit obtained by the household sector from financial institutions, and there are many private loans from Chinese families, including borrowing from relatives and friends, and there is a large-scale hidden debt.
Seeing such data, people can't help but be a little jaw-dropping. According to the statistics of Suning Institute of Finance, the leverage ratio of Chinese residents in 1996 was only 3%, and only 18% in 2008, but the leverage ratio of residents has begun to grow rapidly since 2008, doubling to 36.4% in just six years.
