LONDON, Nov 9 (Reporter Prince Jiang) The British Sports Council on the 9th announced its goal of attending the Pyeongchang Winter Olympics in South Korea next month: winning at least five medals, which is the "most ambitious" goal of the British delegation's participation in the history of the Winter Olympics.
The British Sports Council is responsible for the allocation of funds for various Olympic Games projects, and of course it is responsible for giving medal-winning targets for each project.
It is estimated that the British athletes have the hope of storming medals comes from snowboarding, curling, steel frame snowmobiles and short track speed skating, among other things.
In the past Winter Olympics cycle, the British Sports Council has allocated a total of thirty-two million pounds (£280m) for the Winter Olympics project, which has doubled the cycle of the Winter Olympics.
Most of the money comes from the national lottery, and the rest comes from the state finances.
Britain's hope for winning gold is mainly pinned on the two men, one is last year's world short track speed skating championship three gold medalist Alice Christie, the other is the last women's steel frame snowmobile champion Liz Yaold.
At the 2014 Sochi Winter Olympics, the British delegation achieved a record of 1 gold and silver2 copper, which was the best record they had made since the first Winter Olympics in 1924.
